    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters April 10 with a high-ceiling core, led by **Vinnie Pasquantino** (76.21) and **Mickey Moniak** (75.75), who stand as our premier plays today. **Vinnie Pasquantino** benefits from a massive 17% SP skill boost against a vulnerable Davis Martin, while **Mickey Moniak** leverages a favorable 5.19 xERA matchup against Walker Buehler; the combination of a high-leverage lineup spot and a 90% stolen base opportunity against Buehler\u2019s slow delivery makes **Mickey Moniak** an elite target for both power and our high-priority category, SB. **Brice Turang** (73.40) also earns a strong recommendation, as his #1 lineup spot against the hittable Jake Irvin provides the highest plate appearance floor of the day.\n\nWe are forced to navigate significant lineup uncertainty, as many of our starters are currently \"Lineup Pending.\" The most contentious bench decision involved **Alex Freeland**, who fell just short of the cut at 52.45. While **Alex Freeland** benefits from wind-aided conditions and the same favorable matchup as **Dalton Rushing**, the optimizer prioritized the positional flexibility and higher raw base projection of the active roster. We are also monitoring the risk associated with **Gabriel Moreno** (46.88), who faces an elite arm in Jes\u00fas Luzardo; despite the moderate score, we are keeping him active to maximize volume, though he remains our most volatile play. \n\nStrategic risks include the potential for lower-than-anticipated production from **Max Muncy** and **Tyler Soderstrom**, both facing Clay Holmes. While the matchups are decent, Holmes acts as a stabilizer, and the park factors are slightly suppressed. We are also keeping a close eye on **James Wood** (60.54) and **Jose Caballero** (50.32); while **James Wood** is locked in as a start due to his elite speed profile, **Jose Caballero** is operating near the floor of our utility usage. We will finalize adjustments as official lineups drop, but the path to a 5x5 gain today relies on **Brice Turang** and **Mickey Moniak** exploiting the base-path weaknesses of their respective opponents.",
